    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-08T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-08T15:00:00-05:00" n="474"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d474">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War 1939/1041: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-08T22:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 8, 1943—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1387. In conversation with the British Ambassador<note n="11" xml:id="d474fn11"
                        >Sir H. M. Knatchbull-Hugessen.</note> he said that the Foreign Minister had
                    rejected the suggestion of certain other neutrals for joint action their reply
                    to the American, British and <pb facs="0474" n="464" xml:id="pg_464"/> Soviet
                    notes concerning asylum to war criminals and had advised the Swedish, Swiss and
                    Portuguese Ministers to make “friendly” replies. Hugessen said Numan expressed
                    the opinion that it was “unfortunate” the British note had not followed the form
                    of the American note which was much easier to deal with as it contained no
                    implied threat. Numan promised to discuss with Hugessen the form and substance
                    of the Turkish reply before reaching a final decision, adding that the publicity
                    given the notes had made his position even more difficult. Toward the close of
                    their talk Numan remarked to Hugessen that in any event the Turkish Government
                    would refuse asylum to Mussolini and his henchmen.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
